{
  "texts": [
    "For a large value of J/t 0 = 10, the spin polarization decays to S z c ≈ -1/4, yet with large oscillations.",
    "This behavior is summarized in Fig. 8, where we plot the average long-time value of S z c (t) as a function of J/t 0 and W/t 0.",
    "Overall, disorder suppresses the relaxation and prevents the magnetization transfer.",
    "Note that at small disorder W/t 0, finite-size effects are significant, yet as L increases, a complete relaxation is observed for, e.g., W/t 0 = 0.5 (results not shown here).Generically, we expect Anderson localization for a charge carrier in one dimension, yet coupling to a manybody bath may lift this [80][81][82].",
    "Our data are consistent with localization on finite systems for sufficiently large W/t 0, as disorder detunes possible transitions via the coupling to the spin bath."
  ]
}